# LiVEiT® Accessibility Guidance

Accessibility is a fundamental principle of the LiVEiT® Framework.

Every user should be able to access, understand and interact with LiVEiT® products regardless of ability, technology or environment.

Accessibility should be considered throughout the design and development process rather than added as a final step.

---

# Design Principles

Accessible design within the LiVEiT® Framework is based upon five principles:

* Clarity
* Simplicity
* Consistency
* Inclusivity
* Usability

These principles support a better experience for all users.

---

# Colour and Contrast

Text and interface elements should provide sufficient contrast against their backgrounds.

Recommended practice includes:

* Dark text on light backgrounds.
* Light text on dark backgrounds.
* High contrast for important controls.
* Avoiding low-contrast colour combinations.

Colour should enhance communication rather than reduce readability.

---

# Typography

Typography should remain clear and easy to read.

Recommended practice:

* Use legible fonts.
* Maintain appropriate font sizes.
* Provide adequate line spacing.
* Avoid decorative fonts for body text.
* Preserve clear visual hierarchy.

Readable typography improves accessibility for every user.

---

# Keyboard Navigation

Interactive components should be fully operable using a keyboard where appropriate.

Users should be able to:

* Navigate between controls.
* Activate buttons and links.
* Access menus.
* Close modal windows.
* Move through forms logically.

Visible keyboard focus indicators should always be provided.

---

# Screen Readers

Applications should provide meaningful information to assistive technologies.

Where appropriate:

* Use semantic HTML.
* Provide descriptive labels.
* Include alternative text for informative images.
* Label form controls correctly.
* Use appropriate heading structures.

Content should remain understandable without relying solely on visual presentation.

---

# Icons

Icons should support communication but should not replace descriptive text where understanding may be affected.

Where appropriate:

* Pair icons with labels.
* Provide accessible names.
* Avoid relying solely on colour or icon shape to communicate meaning.

---

# Images

Images should include descriptive alternative text whenever they convey meaningful information.

Decorative images should be ignored by assistive technologies where supported.

Important information should never exist only within an image.

---

# Motion and Animation

Animations should enhance usability without creating unnecessary distraction.

Where possible:

* Respect reduced motion preferences.
* Avoid excessive flashing.
* Keep transitions smooth and purposeful.
* Allow users to complete interactions without time pressure.

Motion should support understanding rather than entertainment.

---

# Responsive Design

Accessible interfaces should function consistently across:

* Desktop computers
* Laptops
* Tablets
* Mobile devices
* High-resolution displays

Layouts should adapt without reducing usability or readability.

---

# Forms

Forms should be easy to complete.

Recommended practice includes:

* Clear labels.
* Helpful instructions.
* Logical field order.
* Meaningful validation messages.
* Accessible error handling.

Users should always understand what information is required.

---

# Documentation

Documentation should be written using clear, concise language.

Where appropriate:

* Use headings to organise content.
* Present information logically.
* Keep paragraphs focused.
* Use lists and tables to improve readability.

Well-structured documentation benefits all users.

---

# Standards

The LiVEiT® Framework aims to support recognised accessibility best practices and encourages developers to design applications that are usable by the widest possible audience.

Projects built using LiVEiT® should consider applicable accessibility standards relevant to their intended platform and audience.

---

# Best Practice

Accessibility is an ongoing responsibility rather than a one-time task.

Every design decision should consider whether it improves clarity, usability and inclusion.

By placing accessibility at the centre of development, the LiVEiT® Framework aims to create technology that is easier for everyone to understand and use.
